Bank Churn Prediction Case Study¶

Problem Definition¶

  • Mostly banks that provide service have to worry about the problem of 'Churn' (customers leaving and joining another service provider). It is important to understand which aspects of the service influence a customer's decision in this regard. Management can concentrate efforts on the improvement of service, keeping in mind these priorities.

Objective¶

  • Given a Bank customer, build a neural network-based classifier that can determine whether they will leave or not in the next 6 months.

  • The dataset contains about 10,000 sample points with 14 distinct features such as CustomerId, CreditScore, Geography, Gender, Age, Tenure, Balance, etc.

Brief Approach¶

  • I have used feature engineering techniques like duplicate items identification, outlier detection and how to deal with them.

  • I'm going to build different neural network models by using differnt layers, dropout and batch-normalization tecquiques to reduce overfit, use early dropout to further optimize the model.

  • I also draw confustion matrix , ROC-AUC curves for each model. Finally I adpoted a best model on test data and drawn conclusions.

  • As a final step I offered my conclusions and recommendations.

# function to create labeled barplots


def labeled_barplot(data, feature, perc=False, n=None):
    """
    Barplot with percentage at the top

    data: dataframe
    feature: dataframe column
    perc: whether to display percentages instead of count (default is False)
    n: displays the top n category levels (default is None, i.e., display all levels)
    """

    total = len(data[feature])  # length of the column
    count = data[feature].nunique()
    if n is None:
        plt.figure(figsize=(count + 1, 5))
    else:
        plt.figure(figsize=(n + 1, 5))

    plt.xticks(rotation=90, fontsize=15)
    ax = sns.countplot(
        data=data,
        x=feature,
        palette="Paired",
        order=data[feature].value_counts().index[:n].sort_values(),
    )

    for p in ax.patches:
        if perc == True:
            label = "{:.1f}%".format(
                100 * p.get_height() / total
            )  # percentage of each class of the category
        else:
            label = p.get_height()  # count of each level of the category

        x = p.get_x() + p.get_width() / 2  # width of the plot
        y = p.get_height()  # height of the plot

        ax.annotate(
            label,
            (x, y),
            ha="center",
            va="center",
            size=12,
            xytext=(0, 5),
            textcoords="offset points",
        )  # annotate the percentage

    plt.show()  # show the plot

# function to plot a boxplot and a histogram along the same scale.


def histogram_boxplot(data, feature, figsize=(12, 7), kde=False, bins=None):
    """
    Boxplot and histogram combined

    data: dataframe
    feature: dataframe column
    figsize: size of figure (default (12,7))
    kde: whether to show the density curve (default False)
    bins: number of bins for histogram (default None)
    """
    f2, (ax_box2, ax_hist2) = plt.subplots(
        nrows=2,  # Number of rows of the subplot grid= 2
        sharex=True,  # x-axis will be shared among all subplots
        gridspec_kw={"height_ratios": (0.25, 0.75)},
        figsize=figsize,
    )  # creating the 2 subplots
    sns.boxplot(
        data=data, x=feature, ax=ax_box2, showmeans=True, color="violet"
    )  # boxplot will be created and a star will indicate the mean value of the column
    sns.histplot(
        data=data, x=feature, kde=kde, ax=ax_hist2, bins=bins, palette="winter"
    ) if bins else sns.histplot(
        data=data, x=feature, kde=kde, ax=ax_hist2
    )  # For histogram
    ax_hist2.axvline(
        data[feature].mean(), color="green", linestyle="--"
    )  # Add mean to the histogram
    ax_hist2.axvline(
        data[feature].median(), color="black", linestyle="-"
    )  # Add median to the histogram

Summary of EDA¶

Data Description:¶

  • Target variable 'Exited': About 80% are existing customers. 20% are Attrited customers.

  • There are no missing values in the dataset.

  • Discussed in length about other columns in the above section.

Data Cleaning:¶

  • Both RowNumber, CustomerId are unique variables so decided to dropped from the data.
  • Surname is also have no impact on building models, hence decided to remove it.
  • After careful consideration, EstimatedSalary column is also removed.

Outliers¶

  • There are 2 customers whose age is 92 and both have estimatedsalary about 100K and balance is about 25K, It seems unusal and decided to remove these two rows.
  • About 233 customers have 850 score which is a perfect score, decided not an outlier and leaving in the data.
  • About 34 customers have balance of 200,000. Who ever having higher balances they are leaving the bank, tend to churn. Again considered this as a market trend and leaving this as it is.
  • Rest of the fields not significantly have any outliers.

Observations from EDA:¶

  • Balance , age are rightly skewed, CreditScore is left skewed.
  • Exited (target variable) is imbalanced (80% are with company, 20% of customers left the company)
  • There is a pattern of customers whose balance is above 100K are tend to leave the bank.
  • France is leading with more than 50% customers, where as Spain and Germany are eqaully shared.
  • Male population is about 55%, Female is around 45%.
  • Majority of cusotomers owning 1 or 2 products. Obvioulst customers who have more products, they have more balance.
  • IsActivemember and HasCrCred features also not have much impact on the target column. But like to keep them to see how models interpret these values.

def make_confusion_matrix(
    cf,
    group_names=None,
    categories="auto",
    count=True,
    percent=True,
    cbar=True,
    xyticks=True,
    xyplotlabels=True,
    sum_stats=True,
    figsize=None,
    cmap="Blues",
    title=None,
):
    """
    This function will make a pretty plot of an sklearn Confusion Matrix cm using a Seaborn heatmap visualization.
    Arguments
    """

    # CODE TO GENERATE TEXT INSIDE EACH SQUARE
    blanks = ["" for i in range(cf.size)]

    if group_names and len(group_names) == cf.size:
        group_labels = ["{}\n".format(value) for value in group_names]
    else:
        group_labels = blanks

    if count:
        group_counts = ["{0:0.0f}\n".format(value) for value in cf.flatten()]
    else:
        group_counts = blanks

    if percent:
        group_percentages = [
            "{0:.2%}".format(value) for value in cf.flatten() / np.sum(cf)
        ]
    else:
        group_percentages = blanks

    box_labels = [
        f"{v1}{v2}{v3}".strip()
        for v1, v2, v3 in zip(group_labels, group_counts, group_percentages)
    ]
    box_labels = np.asarray(box_labels).reshape(cf.shape[0], cf.shape[1])

    # CODE TO GENERATE SUMMARY STATISTICS & TEXT FOR SUMMARY STATS
    if sum_stats:
        # Accuracy is sum of diagonal divided by total observations
        accuracy = np.trace(cf) / float(np.sum(cf))

        # if it is a binary confusion matrix, show some more stats
        if len(cf) == 2:
            # Metrics for Binary Confusion Matrices
            precision = cf[1, 1] / sum(cf[:, 1])
            recall = cf[1, 1] / sum(cf[1, :])
            f1_score = 2 * precision * recall / (precision + recall)
            stats_text = "\n\nAccuracy={:0.3f}\nPrecision={:0.3f}\nRecall={:0.3f}\nF1 Score={:0.3f}".format(
                accuracy, precision, recall, f1_score
            )
        else:
            stats_text = "\n\nAccuracy={:0.3f}".format(accuracy)
    else:
        stats_text = ""

    # SET FIGURE PARAMETERS ACCORDING TO OTHER ARGUMENTS
    if figsize == None:
        # Get default figure size if not set
        figsize = plt.rcParams.get("figure.figsize")

    if xyticks == False:
        # Do not show categories if xyticks is False
        categories = False

    # MAKE THE HEATMAP VISUALIZATION
    plt.figure(figsize=figsize)
    sns.heatmap(
        cf,
        annot=box_labels,
        fmt="",
        cmap=cmap,
        cbar=cbar,
        xticklabels=categories,
        yticklabels=categories,
    )

    if xyplotlabels:
        plt.ylabel("True label")
        plt.xlabel("Predicted label" + stats_text)
    else:
        plt.xlabel(stats_text)

    if title:
        plt.title(title)

)

Model evaluation criterion¶

Model can make wrong predictions as:¶

  • Predicting a customer leaving and joining another service provider (churn) but not happend (not left the company)
  • Predicting a customer not leaving and joining another service provider (churn) but happend (lef the company)

Which case is more important?¶

  • Predicting a customer not leaving and joining another service provider (churn) but happend, which incur a loss to the bank.

How to reduce this loss i.e need to reduce False Negative?¶

  • Company would want Recall to be maximized, greater the Recall higher the chances of minimizing false Negative. Hence, the focus should be on increasing Recall or minimizing the false Negative or in other words identifying the True Positive(i.e. Class 1) so that the Company can identify the fraud transaction.

Conclusion:¶

  • while 82 are predicted as false positive where as 296 identified as false negative.

  • Now I'm going to use other machine learning / deep learning models to check if I can improve this performance

Deep neural network¶
Model-1¶
  • I use a simple NN made of 3 fully-connected layers with ReLu activation. The NN takes a vector of length 10 as input. This represents the information related to each transactions, ie each line with 10 columns from the dataset. For each transaction, the final layer will output a probability distribution (sigmoid activation function) and classify either as not exited (0) or exited (1).
  • I used SGD technique as an optimizer.

Adding layers [layers and activations]¶

  • Keras layers can be added to the model

  • Adding layers are like stacking lego blocks one by one

  • It should be noted that as this is a classification problem, sigmoid layer (softmax for multi-class problems) should be added

In [66]:
# We will be adding the layers sequentially
model_1 = Sequential()

# Adding input layer with 64 neurons, relu as activation function and, he_uniform as weight initializer.
model_1.add(
    Dense(64, activation="relu", kernel_initializer="he_uniform", input_shape=(10,))
)
# Adding the first hidden layer with 32 neurons, relu as activation function and, he_uniform as weight initializer
model_1.add(Dense(32, activation="relu", kernel_initializer="he_uniform"))
# Adding the second hidden layer with 32 neurons, relu as activation function and, he_uniform as weight initializer
model_1.add(Dense(32, activation="relu", kernel_initializer="he_uniform"))

# I use the sigmoid because this is classification problem
model_1.add(Dense(1, activation="sigmoid"))

Observations¶

  • The summary of the model shows each layer's name, type, output shape, and the number of parameters at that particular layer.
  • It also shows the total number of trainable and non-trainable parameters in the model. A parameter whose value is learned while training the model is called a trainable parameter otherwise it is called a non-trainable parameter.
  • In the first layer total parameters are calculated by the number of neurons in the hidden layer multiplied by the number of variables fed to neural networks plus bias. (10*64)+64 = 704
  • In the next layer the parameters are calculated by the number of outputs from the previous layer multiplied by the number of neurons in the second layer plus bias. (64*32)+32 =2080
  • Rest of them we calculate in the same way (32*32)+32 = 1056
  • for output layer (32*1)+1 = 33

# initialize the model_3
model_3 = Sequential()
# This adds the input layer (by specifying input dimension) AND the first hidden layer (units)
model_3.add(
    Dense(units=16, input_dim=10, activation="relu")
)  # input of 29 columns as shown above
# hidden layer
model_3.add(Dense(units=24, activation="relu"))
# Adding Dropout to prevent overfitting
model_3.add(Dropout(0.5))
model_3.add(Dense(24, activation="relu"))
model_3.add(Dense(24, activation="relu"))
# Adding the output layer
# Notice that we do not need to specify input dim.
# we have an output of 1 node, which is the the desired dimensions of our output (fraud or not)
# We use the sigmoid because we want probability outcomes
model_3.add(Dense(1, activation="sigmoid"))  # binary classification fraudulent or not

# Initializing the model
model_4 = Sequential()
# Adding input layer with 64 neurons, relu as activation function and, he_uniform as weight initializer.
model_4.add(
    Dense(64, activation="relu", kernel_initializer="he_uniform", input_shape=(10,))
)
# Adding the first hidden layer with 32 neurons, relu as activation function and, he_uniform as weight initializer
model_4.add(Dense(32, activation="relu", kernel_initializer="he_uniform"))
# Adding Batch Normalization
model_4.add(BatchNormalization())
# Adding the second hidden layer with 32 neurons, relu as activation function and, he_uniform as weight initializer
model_4.add(Dense(32, activation="relu", kernel_initializer="he_uniform"))
# We use the sigmoid because we want probability outcomes
model_4.add(Dense(1, activation="sigmoid"))  # binary classification fraudulent or not

Model-5¶
  • I'm going to use a NN made of 4 fully-connected layers with ReLu activation. The NN takes a vector of length 10 as input. This represents the information related to each transactions, ie each line with 10 columns from the dataset. For each transaction, the final layer will output a probability distribution (sigmoid activation function) and classify either as not exited (0) or exited (1).
  • I'm goint to try both BatchNormalization and dropout techniques and see if I can improve the metrics.
  • And, I used Adam optimizer
  • Also applied early stop technique too.

# Initializing the model
model_5 = Sequential()
# Adding input layer with 64 neurons, relu as activation function and, he_uniform as weight initializer.
model_5.add(
    Dense(64, activation="relu", kernel_initializer="he_uniform", input_shape=(10,))
)
# Adding dropout with ratio of 0.1
model_5.add(Dropout(0.2))
# Adding the first hidden layer with 32 neurons, relu as activation function and, he_uniform as weight initializer
model_5.add(Dense(32, activation="relu", kernel_initializer="he_uniform"))
# Adding dropout with ratio of 0.1
model_5.add(Dropout(0.1))
# Adding the second hidden layer with 16 neurons, relu as activation function and, he_uniform as weight initializer
model_5.add(Dense(16, activation="relu", kernel_initializer="he_uniform"))
# Adding Batch Normalization
model_5.add(BatchNormalization())
# Adding the third hidden layer with 8 neurons, relu as activation function and, he_uniform as weight initializer
model_5.add(Dense(8, activation="relu", kernel_initializer="he_uniform"))
# We use the sigmoid because we want probability outcomes
model_5.add(Dense(1, activation="sigmoid"))  # binary classification fraudulent or not

Conclusions¶

  • I trained 5 different models with some changes in architecture and Optimizer, for example by changing the number of dense layers, learning rate, number of neurons in hidden layers, optimyzer types (SGD or Adam with /without learning rate)
  • I have also used dropout, batch-nomralization, early dropout etc.
  • Almost all models have some sort of overfitting. I adpoted best model on test data. Still False negatives are not gone down significantly. The recall is around 0.480 on test data.
  • Like I mentioned in the EDA, since we know customers who have more balance are leaving the bank(churn). Bank should focus on these cutomers who have more than 100k balance (the count is about 3500) by adapting various marketting techniques and try their best to retain them.
  • The marketting ideas including but not limited to : Talk to individual customers and understand their needs, offer payment plan, pause the payment for few months, Offer discount if they are willing to pay the whole amount. Offer 0(zero) discount on the balance. Certainly these techniques would help bank to stop customers churn!
